Security Practices:
1. Installing Anti-virus program:
  I do not have a third party Anti-Virus protection against malware. 
  I have a mac and the protection is built in. The three defense systems used are  Notarization,
  and X protect. Before a developer can put their apps up for distirbution outside of the app store, apple scans the software and if no malware 
  is detected then a notarized ticket is issued, showig that the app is safe and allowed to be distributed.
  XProtect is run automaticaly whenever a user opens up the app to check for any malware signatures. No manual updates are needed from the user, this antivirus protection from the mac updates and scans automatically.
2. Avoiding Suspicious emails:  
  I have received emails in the past that I suspected had infected content. 
  There are many antivirus options, Norton 360 and Avast Premium Security- These third party options 
  scan the email and flag for any phishing or scams for the user. 
  Gmail/ Outlook and microsoft 360 automatically scan the emails for suspicious content and senders as well. 

3. Installing patches to operating system and browser:
  In my mac, Software Update in System Settings auto installs updates on patches. 
  In my browser, I use chrome and the patches updates in the background.

4. Install and run Spyware/Adware software.
  For apple, other than using Tracking Permissions which limits what apps can track, the mac uses the built in original antivirus protections.

5. Firwall:
  Mac has a built in firewall that blocks all unauthorized apps and programs from accepting incoming connections. 
  I checked by system setting network and I did not have firewall turned on. I most definitly turned the firewall on.








